               <history>
                  <origin>
                     <origDate calendar="Gregorian" when="1470" cert="high">1470</origDate>
                     <origPlace>
                        <country key="place_1000080">Italy</country>, <settlement key="place_7004264">Ferrara</settlement> (fols 1–19)</origPlace>; 
                     <origPlace>
                        <country key="place_1000070">France</country>
                     </origPlace>
                     <!--MULTIPLE PLACES OF ORIGIN-->
                  </origin>
                  
                  <provenance>The colophon (dated 1470 CE) on fol. 436 states that the book was written and illuminated for <persName role="fmo">'Ioannes Baptista' de Girardis (Gherardo)</persName>, born at Bologna 
                     and canon of St Peter's at Rome: 'Mille quadringentis domini si iunxeris: unde / Septuagesima annos: tempora nostra scies'</provenance>
                  
                  <!-- Add authority record -->   
                  
                  <provenance>Pächt and Alexander (<ref target="https://catalog.hathitrust.org/Record/000468709">ii. 913</ref>) assign fols 1r-19v to Ferrara, and the manuscript may have been written there, but the rest of the manuscript's decoration was possibly 
                     completed in France (Watson, 1984, no. 282)</provenance>
                  
                  <provenance >On <ref target="https://digital.bodleian.ox.ac.uk/objects/30018003-7122-4c25-8dc2-c196afc2e6e4/surfaces/90229b13-6512-4086-bdde-a2c371f5381f/">fol. 258a</ref> 
                     arms have been erased but an offset of them on the preceding page almost certainly shows them to be those of Gonzaga, possibly of
                     Cardinal Francesco Gonzaga (Watson, 1984, no. 282)</provenance>
                  <provenance>Unidentified arms, fols 205v and 356r: azure a leopard salient per fess or and sable, overall a baston gules</provenance>
                  <provenance>No. 7914 in the <persName role="fmo" key="person_41829393">Maffei Pinelli</persName> catalogue of 1787 and no. 12820 in the Pinelli sale catalogue of 1789 
                     (the poem is printed in the catalogue, with a full description). Bought at the sale for £32 6s. by - Kearney</provenance> 
                  
                  <provenance><persName key="person_2384880" role="fmo">Matteo Luigi Canonici (1727– <hi rend="italic">c</hi>. 1806)</persName></provenance>
                  <provenance notAfter="1807" resp="#SC">Following Canonici's death, the collection passed to his brother, <persName key="person_446" role="fmo">Giuseppe Canonici</persName>, and 
                     then to Canonici's nephew, <persName role="fmo" key="person_431">Giovanni Perissinotti</persName>, in 1807 following Giuseppe Canonici's death</provenance>
                  <acquisition when="1817">Bought by the Bodleian Library in 1817 from Giovanni Perissinotti. On the purchase, see <ref target="https://digital.bodleian.ox.ac.uk/collections/canonici/">Digital Bodleian</ref></acquisition>
                  
               </history>
